BillW is correct.  A fair number of KA-10 and KI-10 systems WERE front-ended
by PDP-8s.  (In this context, "front end" means "the device that you connect
all your async terminals to" and not "the thing that loads microcode".)

SCNSER had support for <DATAI DLS,AC> to read from the DC10 Data Line Scanner
and from PDP-8 based devices on the CCI (Computer to Computer Interface,
I/O device 14).

At the Colorado School of Mines, we had a PDP-8 serving all the ASR-33 TTY
lines.  We had things set up such that the PDP-10 could boot from the PDP-8.

Well, almost.  The usual way of booting a KA was to boot from paper tape,
using a short program in the paper tape reader that would read a larger
BOOTS program off the first few blocks of the RP02.  The pre-boot program
wasn't very big, an we were able to store it in an unused section of the
PDP-8's memory.  If you set the Read-In Mode switches to 014 (CCI) instead
of 104 (PTR), the short boot program would be entered into the PDP-10's
memory from the 8 instead of from paper tape.

>but memory is getting fuzzy.  And I worked on them!
>-- 
>Eric (Ric) Werme         |  werme@zk3.dec.com
>Digital Equipment Corp.  |  This space intentionally left blank.

